{"questionId":"17366","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Points <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"{\\text{A}}\">\n  <mrow>\n    <mtext>A</mtext>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span>(0 , 0 , 10) , <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"{\\text{B}}\">\n  <mrow>\n    <mtext>B</mtext>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span>(0 , 10 , 0) , <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"{\\text{C}}\">\n  <mrow>\n    <mtext>C</mtext>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span>(10 , 0 , 0) , <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"{\\text{V}}\">\n  <mrow>\n    <mtext>V</mtext>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span>(<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"p\">\n  <mi>p</mi>\n</math></span> , <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"p\">\n  <mi>p</mi>\n</math></span> , <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"p\">\n  <mi>p</mi>\n</math></span>) form the vertices of a tetrahedron.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The following diagram shows the graph of <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"\\theta \">\n  <mi>θ</mi>\n</math></span> against <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"p\">\n  <mi>p</mi>\n</math></span>. The maximum point is shown by <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"{\\text{X}}\">\n  <mrow>\n    <mtext>X</mtext>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span>.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/0b394f4344b4cb92f260a88774a80facff29350a.png\"></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Find the equation of the horizontal asymptote of the graph.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"p \\to \\infty&nbsp; \\Rightarrow {\\text{cos}}\\,\\theta&nbsp; \\to \\frac{1}{2}\"> <mi>p</mi> <mo stretchy=\"false\">→</mo> <mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi> <mo stretchy=\"false\">⇒</mo> <mrow> <mtext>cos</mtext> </mrow> <mspace width=\"thinmathspace\"></mspace> <mi>θ</mi> <mo stretchy=\"false\">→</mo> <mfrac> <mn>1</mn> <mn>2</mn> </mfrac> </math></span>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>M1</strong></em></p>\n<p>hence the asymptote has equation <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"\\theta&nbsp; = \\frac{\\pi }{3}\"> <mi>θ</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mi>π</mi> <mn>3</mn> </mfrac> </math></span>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>&nbsp; &nbsp;A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><em><strong>[2 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"17366","referenceCode":"19N.1.AHL.TZ0.H_11c.ii","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Find the equation of the horizontal asymptote of the graph.","paper":"1","level":"HL","questionNumber":"c.ii","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","AHL 3.18—Intersections of lines & planes"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}